questionRound.0.question.9.answer: The right-hand-most player always had one decision that would optimize their earnings  since their payoff was set up so that the lowest possible payoff for either X or Y would give them more than the highest possible payoff for the other choice. Therefore the right-hand player was the "independent variable" whose decision would not be influenced by the other players at all. I assumed the other players would realize that quickly enough and follow the chain of payoff possibilities starting from the right-hand player's X or Y choice and choose the option that would give them highest payoff based on the choice made by the player to their right. I stopped looking when I got to my square.

There was always a row in one of the colors that had higher numbers than those the other row so you automatically know which row the person with that color would choose and you work backwards from there till you get to your own color.

I was playing based off of what numbers had a better payoff for me and also based off of how I thought another color would affect my payoff. Lastly I considered how I would affect another color. I just oplayed based off of what I thought would get me a better pay off  sometimes it was clear which would give me a better pay off  other times I took risks hoping it would give me a better pay off.

The person who had the easiest decision to make  in this given match Green  would choose the one that was obviously beneficial (XG).  Blue would see this and choose his best bet that goes with XG  in this case YB.  Then Red would choose the best choice to go with YB  which is XR.  Then myself  as Orange  would hope that everyone else did this and choose the corresponding and most beneficial option  which in my case ended up being XO.  This worked for me everytime once I figured it out; you just have to find the person with the obvious decision and go from there.

First I would look at the pay amounts of each of the four boxes under my payoff.  I would then pick the box with the highest amount.  But before picking said box I would check what was the option that the other color that I was depending on would have to pick  either the X or the Y.  Then I would look at the pay amounts of that color's box.  If the highest numbers were in the line that I needed that color to chose I would pick my first option. But only after checking the pay amounts of all the other colors and thinking about what lines each was most likely to choose and how their decisions could affect me.  Sometimes it was best to go for the second highest number instead of risking getting the lowest pay amount.

questionRound.0.question.9.answer: I began by first chosing a block that my opponent would think I was going to choose from the first column of my color. With my choice I would then move unto the next color payout that was dependent on my choice. From there I would select the highest token value assuming my opponents would always target those numbers. Next I would move unto the next color with the targeted choice from the last color. I would do this until the last color  which my payout was dependent on and from there I chose the highest of the two values in the certain row/column I hypothesized my opponent would choose.

I would go through each color's payoffs and logically guess which option they would choose  working backwards until I came full circle back to the color I was assigned.  |  | I would additionally take into account which of my two options would yield the highest payoff.

Basically I use the knowledge I learnt from game theory. I will often look at my pay off box first  see which player 's action will affect me. So I will analyze which one he will choose and make my own decision. Sometimes it's hard to predict one hundred percent right since some players may not try to maximize their profits

The player on the far right is given two options; one option is the clear choice because the smaller number is larger than the larger number for the second option.  By moving left  it is clear what each other player should choose to maximize their payoff.

By the second/third game I noticed there was always a "strongest link' among the players... in which the choice to take x or y was obvious. From there I would back track or forward track through each linked player until reaching my own and choosing the best choice for myself in respect to the other players.

If one of the choices that I could have made would give more tokens regardless of that someone else chose  then I would choose that one. For example  of the top row of one of the boxes was 30 and 20 and the bottom row was 10 and 15  i would choose the top becuase no matter what it was the best choice. Also i would choose what would seem like higher choice every other time  unless the first thing i noticed was occuring.
